      "id": "tibialis-raises",
      "name": "Tibialis Anterior Raises",
      "sets": "3Г—15",
      "notes": "Stand with back against wall, feet ~12 inches out. Pull toes up toward shins, lower slowly. This strengthens the front of your shin and protects the knee. The Knees Over Toes Guy made this famous for good reason.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=tibialis+raises+knees+over+toes+tutorial",
      "searchTerms": "Tibialis raises Knees Over Toes"
    },
    {
      "id": "banded-tke",
      "name": "Banded Terminal Knee Extensions",
      "sets": "3Г—15 each leg",
      "notes": "Attach band behind your knee to a low anchor. Stand facing away, slight bend. Squeeze to full lockout against band resistance. This isolates the VMO вҖ” the inner quad muscle that stabilizes the kneecap.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=banded+terminal+knee+extension+VMO",
      "searchTerms": "Banded TKE VMO strengthening"
    },
    {
      "id": "atg-split-squat",
      "name": "ATG Split Squat (Regressed)",
      "sets": "3Г—8 each leg",
      "notes": "Start with hands on bench/chair for support. Back knee tracks all the way down and forward. ONLY go as deep as you can control without pain. Weeks 1-2: use support. Weeks 3-4: reduce support. This is the single best knee bulletproofing exercise.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=ATG+split+squat+regression+beginner+knees+over+toes",
      "searchTerms": "ATG split squat beginner regression",
      "progressionByPhase": {
        "Foundation": { "sets": "3Г—8 each leg", "notes": "Use bench support, partial depth only." },
        "Build": { "sets": "3Г—8 each leg", "notes": "Reduce bench support, increase depth." },
        "Load": { "sets": "3Г—8 each leg", "notes": "Light dumbbells, no support." }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "cossack-squat",
      "name": "Cossack Squat (Partial ROM)",
      "sets": "3Г—6 each side",
      "notes": "Bodyweight only. Start with a small range вҖ” you do NOT need to go ass-to-grass. Hold a doorframe or rack for balance. This directly trains the lateral movement pattern that's giving your knees trouble. Depth will come with consistency.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=cossack+squat+beginner+progression+mobility",
      "searchTerms": "Cossack squat progression beginner",
      "progressionByPhase": {
        "Foundation": { "sets": "3Г—6 each side", "notes": "Hold doorframe, go only as deep as comfortable." },
        "Build": { "sets": "3Г—6 each side", "notes": "Less support, aim for parallel thigh depth." },
        "Load": { "sets": "3Г—6 each side", "notes": "Goblet Cossack Squats with light dumbbell." }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "active-frog-stretch",
      "name": "Active Frog Stretch",
      "sets": "2Г—45 sec",
      "notes": "On all fours, knees wide, rock forward and back. Keep spine neutral. This opens the adductors (inner thigh) which are contributing to both your lateral lunge pain and cross-legged sitting difficulty. Active rocking > static hold.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=active+frog+stretch+hip+adductor+mobility",
      "searchTerms": "Active frog stretch adductors"
    },
    {
      "id": "copenhagen-plank-b",
      "name": "Copenhagen Plank",
      "sets": "3Г—15-20 sec each side",
      "notes": "Side plank position with top leg on a bench, bottom leg hanging free. This is a two-for-one вҖ” it trains lateral core strength AND adductor strength simultaneously. Directly addresses your lateral lunge knee pain. Regress by using bottom knee on the floor or shortening the hold. These are brutally hard at first вҖ” 10 seconds is fine to start.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=copenhagen+plank+tutorial+regression+progression",
      "searchTerms": "Copenhagen plank tutorial progression",
      "tags": ["core-integration"]
    }
  ]
},
{
  "id": "ankle-integration",
  "title": "Session C: Ankle/Achilles & Integration",
  "subtitle": "15-20 min вҖ” Do 1-2x per week",
  "description": "Your repaired Achilles needs consistent eccentric loading to stay resilient вҖ” this is backed by decades of research (Alfredson protocol). Combined with dorsiflexion work, this session protects the ankle and unlocks deeper squat positions. The balance work re-trains proprioception that was disrupted by the surgery.",
  "sortOrder": 4,
  "color": "rgb(180, 140, 224)",
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "extended-ankle-cars",
      "name": "Extended Ankle CARs",
      "sets": "2Г—8 each direction, each foot",
      "notes": "Slower and more deliberate than your daily CARs. Spend 5+ seconds per rotation on the right ankle. Map out the full range, note where it catches. Over weeks, the circle should get bigger.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=ankle+CARs+FRC+detailed+tutorial",
      "searchTerms": "Ankle CARs detailed FRC"
    },
    {
      "id": "eccentric-calf-raises",
      "name": "Eccentric Calf Raises (Alfredson Protocol)",
      "sets": "3Г—15 each leg",
      "notes": "CRITICAL for your Achilles. Stand on step edge, raise up on BOTH feet, then lower slowly (3-4 sec) on ONE foot. Do both straight-knee (gastroc) and bent-knee (soleus) versions. The right side may feel tight вҖ” stay in a pain-free range. This is the gold standard for Achilles tendon health.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=eccentric+calf+raises+achilles+alfredson+protocol",
      "searchTerms": "Eccentric calf raises Alfredson Achilles",
      "progressionByPhase": {
        "Foundation": { "notes": "Both-leg lower if single-leg is too intense on the right." },
        "Build": { "notes": "Full single-leg protocol." }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "wall-dorsiflexion",
      "name": "Wall Dorsiflexion Mobilization",
      "sets": "3Г—30 sec each side",
      "notes": "Face wall, foot ~4 inches away. Drive knee forward over toes, keeping heel DOWN. Measure progress by how far from the wall you can get your foot while still touching knee to wall. Your right side will be tighter вҖ” that's the Achilles repair limiting dorsiflexion.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=wall+ankle+dorsiflexion+mobilization+test",
      "searchTerms": "Wall dorsiflexion ankle mobilization"
    },
    {
      "id": "single-leg-balance",
      "name": "Single-Leg Balance (Eyes Closed)",
      "sets": "3Г—30 sec each leg",
      "notes": "Start with eyes open if needed. Bare feet on firm surface. The goal is rebuilding proprioception in the repaired ankle. If 30s is easy with eyes closed, try it on a folded towel for an unstable surface.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=single+leg+balance+proprioception+ankle+rehab",
      "searchTerms": "Single leg balance proprioception",
      "progressionByPhase": {
        "Load": { "notes": "Single-leg balance on unstable surface (folded towel or pillow)." }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "supported-deep-squat",
      "name": "Supported Deep Squat Hold",
      "sets": "3Г—30-45 sec",
      "notes": "Hold a doorframe, squat rack, or heavy dumbbell as counterbalance. Sink as deep as comfortable, heels down. Let your hips open and spine lengthen. This integrates ankle, knee, and hip mobility into one functional position. If heels lift, elevate them on a plate or book.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=deep+squat+hold+mobility+assisted+progression",
      "searchTerms": "Deep squat hold assisted mobility",
      "progressionByPhase": {
        "Load": { "notes": "Weighted deep squat holds (goblet position)." }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "dead-bugs-c",
      "name": "Dead Bugs",
      "sets": "3Г—8 each side",
      "notes": "Lie on your back, arms up, knees at 90В°. Press lower back into floor. Slowly extend opposite arm and leg while maintaining ZERO low back movement. If your back arches, you've gone too far вҖ” shorten the range. This trains anti-extension and hip dissociation, directly improving your squat and overhead positions.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=dead+bug+exercise+tutorial+anti+extension",
      "searchTerms": "Dead bug exercise anti-extension",
      "tags": ["core-integration"]
    },
    {
      "id": "bear-crawl",
      "name": "Bear Crawl",
      "sets": "2Г—30 sec",
      "notes": "Hands and feet on ground, knees hovering ~2 inches off floor. Crawl forward and backward slowly. This integrates shoulder stability, hip mobility, and ankle mobility under load in a way that mimics real-world movement. Keep breathing.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=bear+crawl+exercise+mobility+tutorial",
      "searchTerms": "Bear crawl exercise mobility"
    }
  ]
},
{
  "id": "core-stability",
  "title": "Session D: Core Stability",
  "subtitle": "15-20 min вҖ” Do 1-2x per week",
  "description": "Your shoulders, knees, and ankles all depend on a stable trunk. When the core can't hold position, your joints compensate вҖ” that's a big part of why you keep getting injured. This session trains anti-extension, anti-rotation, and anti-lateral-flexion вҖ” the three pillars of functional core stability. These aren't crunches; they teach your core to resist unwanted movement so your limbs can move freely. Exercises marked with \u25c6 in other sessions are drawn from here.",
  "sortOrder": 5,
  "color": "rgb(224, 120, 150)",
  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "dead-bugs-d",
      "name": "Dead Bugs",
      "sets": "3Г—10 each side",
      "notes": "The king of core exercises for your situation. Lie on back, arms up, knees at 90В°. Press lower back into floor вҖ” this is the cue that matters. Extend opposite arm and leg while maintaining ZERO low back movement. Slow and controlled вҖ” 3 seconds out, 3 seconds back. If your back arches, shorten the range. Progress by holding a light dumbbell overhead or adding a band around your feet.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=dead+bug+exercise+tutorial+progression",
      "searchTerms": "Dead bug exercise progression"
    },
    {
      "id": "pallof-press",
      "name": "Pallof Press",
      "sets": "3Г—10 each side",
      "notes": "Attach band to anchor at chest height. Stand sideways, hold band at chest. Press straight out and hold 2 seconds. The band tries to rotate you вҖ” your core resists. This anti-rotation strength directly supports your Cossack squats and lateral lunge stability. Keep hips square, don't let the band pull you.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=pallof+press+band+anti+rotation+core",
      "searchTerms": "Pallof press band tutorial"
    },
    {
      "id": "bird-dogs",
      "name": "Bird Dogs",
      "sets": "3Г—8 each side",
      "notes": "On all fours, extend opposite arm and leg simultaneously. Hold top position for 2 seconds. Keep hips LEVEL вҖ” the most common mistake is letting the hip drop on the lifting side. Place a water bottle on your lower back as feedback вҖ” if it falls, you're rotating too much. This trains the cross-body stabilization pattern used in walking, running, and all unilateral exercises.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=bird+dog+exercise+proper+form+tutorial",
      "searchTerms": "Bird dog exercise proper form"
    },
    {
      "id": "hollow-body-hold-d",
      "name": "Hollow Body Hold",
      "sets": "3Г—30 sec",
      "notes": "Arms overhead, legs extended, low back pressed into floor, shoulders and feet lifted. Scale it: bent knees with arms at sides (easiest) \u2192 straight legs with arms at sides \u2192 straight legs with arms overhead (hardest). If you can hold 30s at the hardest version, you can progress to hollow body rocks.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=hollow+body+hold+tutorial+progression+beginner",
      "searchTerms": "Hollow body hold progression"
    },
    {
      "id": "copenhagen-plank-d",
      "name": "Copenhagen Plank",
      "sets": "3Г—20-30 sec each side",
      "notes": "Side plank with top leg on bench, bottom leg free. Trains lateral core and adductors simultaneously. Regression: bend bottom knee to floor, or use a shorter bench so you're supporting from the knee instead of the foot. Progression: add hip dips (lower and lift hips while holding). This exercise alone can fix a lot of your lateral movement issues.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=copenhagen+plank+tutorial+regression+progression",
      "searchTerms": "Copenhagen plank tutorial"
    },
    {
      "id": "suitcase-carry",
      "name": "Suitcase Carry",
      "sets": "3Г—30 sec each side",
      "notes": "Hold a single dumbbell at your side (moderate weight вҖ” 25-40 lb range), walk slowly. Keep your trunk PERFECTLY upright вҖ” don't lean away from the weight. This trains anti-lateral-flexion and grip strength simultaneously. You'll feel your obliques and deep stabilizers light up. Walk slowly and deliberately, don't rush.",
      "videoURL": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=suitcase+carry+exercise+anti+lateral+flexion",
      "searchTerms": "Suitcase carry anti-lateral flexion"
    }
  ]
},
{
  "id": "active-recovery",
  "title": "Active Recovery",
  "subtitle": "20-30 min вҖ” Do 1-2x per week",
  "description": "Easy effort only. The purpose is blood flow, not fitness. If you find yourself breathing hard on the bike, you're going too hard. Pair with foam rolling to address tissue quality.",

    },
